To specifically detect navigation events, you should utilize a `Navigator` observer. You can create a custom `NavigatorObserver` and override the `didPush`, `didPop`, or other methods to perform actions when navigating between routes. This way, you'll be informed precisely when a route is pushed or popped, and you can execute your desired logic.

Here's an example using a `NavigatorObserver` in a `HookWidget`:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:flutter_hooks/flutter_hooks.dart';

class MyNavigatorObserver extends NavigatorObserver {
  @override
  void didPop(Route<dynamic> route, Route<dynamic>? previousRoute) {
    // Perform work when navigating back to the previous route
    print('Navigated back to: ${previousRoute?.settings.name}');
  }

  @override
  void didPush(Route<dynamic> route, Route<dynamic>? previousRoute) {
    // Perform work when a new route is pushed
    print('Pushed route: ${route.settings.name}');
  }
}

class MyHookWidget extends HookWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      navigatorObservers: [MyNavigatorObserver()],
      home: Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(title: Text('My App')),
        body: Center(
          child: ElevatedButton(
            child: Text('Go to Next Page'),
            onPressed: () {
              Navigator.push(context, MaterialPageRoute(
                builder: (context) => NextPage(),
                settings: RouteSettings(name: 'NextPage'),
              ));
            },
          ),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

class NextPage extends HookWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: Text('Next Page')),
      body: Center(child: Text('Welcome to the next page!')),
    );
  }
}
```

In this setup:
- A `MyNavigatorObserver` class is created to handle navigation events.
- You override `didPop` to execute logic when going back to a previous route and `didPush` for when a new route is pushed.
- Add the observer to your `MaterialApp`.

Using this method, you can safely detect navigation actions without worrying about the app lifecycle events interfering or being called multiple times unnecessarily.

In Flutter, when dealing with multiple levels of navigation, such as nested navigators with a tab bar, you will want to use multiple `NavigatorObserver` instances. Each observer can be assigned to their respective navigator, allowing you to handle navigation events more granularly at each level.

### Approach:

1. **Use a Single Observer for Each Navigator**: Each navigator (e.g., the main navigator, tab navigators, and any nested navigators) can have its own `NavigatorObserver`. This allows you to separately track events on each level of navigation.

2. **Pass Observers to Each Navigator**: When you create a `Navigator`, you can specify the observer for that specific navigator. 

### Example:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class MainNavigatorObserver extends NavigatorObserver {
  @override
  void didPush(Route<dynamic> route, Route<dynamic>? previousRoute) {
    print('Main Navigator: Pushed route: ${route.settings.name}');
  }

  @override
  void didPop(Route<dynamic> route, Route<dynamic>? previousRoute) {
    print('Main Navigator: Navigated back to: ${previousRoute?.settings.name}');
  }
}

class TabNavigatorObserver extends NavigatorObserver {
  @override
  void didPush(Route<dynamic> route, Route<dynamic>? previousRoute) {
    print('Tab Navigator: Pushed route: ${route.settings.name}');
  }

  @override
  void didPop(Route<dynamic> route, Route<dynamic>? previousRoute) {
    print('Tab Navigator: Navigated back to: ${previousRoute?.settings.name}');
  }
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      home: MainPage(),
      navigatorObservers: [MainNavigatorObserver()], // Main observer
    );
  }
}

class MainPage extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return DefaultTabController(
      length: 2,
      child: Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(
          title: Text('Tabs'),
          bottom: TabBar(
            tabs: [
              Tab(text: 'Tab 1'),
              Tab(text: 'Tab 2'),
            ],
          ),
        ),
        body: TabBarView(
          children: [
            Tab1Navigator(), // First Tab with its own Navigator
            Center(child: Text('Tab 2 Content')),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

class Tab1Navigator extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Navigator(
      observers: [TabNavigatorObserver()], // Tab observer
      onGenerateRoute: (RouteSettings settings) {
        return MaterialPageRoute(
          builder: (context) => FirstPage(),
          settings: settings,
        );
      },
    );
  }
}

class FirstPage extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: Text('First Page')),
      body: Center(
        child: ElevatedButton(
          child: Text('Go to Second Page'),
          onPressed: () {
            Navigator.push(
              context,
              MaterialPageRoute(
                  builder: (context) => SecondPage(),
                  settings: RouteSettings(name: 'SecondPage')),
            );
          },
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

class SecondPage extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: Text('Second Page')),
      body: Center(child: Text('Welcome to the second page!')),
    );
  }
}

void main() {
  runApp(MyApp());
}
```

### Explanation:
- **MainNavigatorObserver** is used for the main navigation stack (this could be a stack of pages).
- **TabNavigatorObserver** is specific to the tab inside the main navigator.
- Each `Navigator` can have its respective observer, allowing you to track navigation actions independently.

### Conclusion:
Using multiple observers provides you with fine-grained control over navigation events at each stack level. It’s a flexible approach that keeps concerns separated.

